'''Booie''' is a rural [[suburbs and localities (Australia)|locality]] on the boundary of Kingaroy and Nanango in the [[South Burnett Region]], [[Queensland]], Australia.<ref name=qpn>{{cite QPN|46196|Booie|accessdate=26 April 2014}}</ref> In the [[census in Australia#2011|2011 census]], the population was 912 people.<ref name="ABS">{{Census 2011 AUS|id= SSC30198 |name=Booie (SSC)|accessdate=26 April 2014|quick=on}}</ref>

==History==
The name ''Booie'' derives from the name of a pastoral run, which is believed to be a [[Wakawaka language]] word meaning  ''carpet snake''.<ref name=qpn/>

A provisional school had been established by 1893.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article123344658 |title=The West Moreton State Schools. |newspaper=[[Queensland Times, Ipswich Herald & General Advertiser]] |date=10 June 1893 |accessdate=27 April 2014 |page=7 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> In 1905, a new Booie State School was erected.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article20798079 |title=NEW STATE SCHOOLS. |newspaper=[[The Queenslander]] |date=16 September 1905 |accessdate=27 April 2014 |page=38 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Booie State School closed in 1963.<ref name=qs>{{Cite QldSchool|accessdate=26 April 2014}}</ref>

==Booie Monster==
In June 1954, Booie hit the news after local boys claimed to have seen a two-legged monster in a cave. Despite searching by experienced bushman, the monster was not found and it was speculated that the boys had seen a large kangaroo.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article76239518 |title=MYSTERY OF "CAVE MONSTER" AT KINGAROY. |newspaper=[[The Central Queensland Herald]] |location=Rockhampton, Qld. |date=10 June 1954 |accessdate=27 April 2014 |page=16 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>

